2





455 Golden Gate AveSan Francisco, CA 94102


        (415) 255-8105
    






So far, so good.  Yes, I pay for the convenience of a 30 min charge on my leaf.  But I dont need to install a charger at home. I use a combination of fast charging and 120v slow at home.  And it works better than if I spent money to put 240v at home.







I have charged my car with electricity at NRG eVgo four times.  Electricity costs me 18.15 cents per kwh at home, sometimes a little more and sometimes a little less.  In contrast at NRG eVgo, I have to pay a charge which is nominally $1.50 per hour of time.  The electricity flows to my car at only 1.95 kw, or at 1/2 kw in the last half of the charging session.  The time seems to be rounded up to the next half hour.  So, to make it simple, I end up paying around $1.00 per kwh when at home the electricity sells for about 1/5 as much.  It is also less than at other charging stations.

I realize that NRG eVgo does have expenses, but the prices discourage me from charging.  The prices might not even be profit maximizing from theNRG eVgo standpoint, since I can honestly state that I have never once seen any other vehicle charging at the Level 2 charging station.

I realize that the NRG eVgo charging station is a convenience, but the price premium seems too much of a premium from my standpoint.

If the prices were stated as X per kwh, I would likely make more use of NRG eVgo.







            Nrg Energy
        






