        2/17/2016
    








First to Review
        


I have charged my car with electricity at NRG eVgo four times.  Electricity costs me 18.15 cents per kwh at home, sometimes a little more and sometimes a little less.  In contrast at NRG eVgo, I have to pay a charge which is nominally $1.50 per hour of time.  The electricity flows to my car at only 1.95 kw, or at 1/2 kw in the last half of the charging session.  The time seems to be rounded up to the next half hour.  So, to make it simple, I end up paying around $1.00 per kwh when at home the electricity sells for about 1/5 as much.  It is also less than at other charging stations.I realize that NRG eVgo does have expenses, but the prices discourage me from charging.  The prices might not even be profit maximizing from theNRG eVgo standpoint, since I can honestly state that I have never once seen any other vehicle charging at the Level 2 charging station.I realize that the NRG eVgo charging station is a convenience, but the price premium seems too much of a premium from my standpoint.If the prices were stated as X per kwh, I would likely make more use of NRG eVgo.




